        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>See proposal text for further details

The observations will target the optically thin Rayleigh Jeans tail of the dust emission from which we infer gas masses via the gas-to-dust ratio (Scoville et al. 2013). We note that massive cluster galaxies have solar abundances or greater (see Loubser et al. 2009) and our targets have high stellar masses (&gt;1e11Msol) therefore the Scoville et al. (2013) gas-to-dust formulae apply. In Fig 2. we calculate the ALMA Band 7 continuum flux corresponding to gas masses of 0.5-2e10Msol (which covers the range of gas mass values per resolution element we discuss in the proposal) utilising the equations of Scoville et al. (2013). The flux per resolution element to map the extended cold gas emission over the entire 7'' sq. region corresponding to Mgas=0.6e10Msol is 0.33 mJy and this is the what we aim to measure to the 5 sigma level.

Using the ALMA observing tool, integration time calculator we find that in a 9.4 minute, on target, Band 7 observation we can probe down to an inferred gas mass of Mgas=0.6e10Msol to a significance of 5 sigma (flux=0.33mJy, 1 sigma=0.066mJy). This means we can easily probe the distribution of the gas throughout the 7'' sq. region containing the all four galaxies at our requested resolution of 0.5'' (4 kpc) in order to look for extended emission linking the galaxies. With overheads and calibrations this adds up to a total time of 40 minutes. 
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
