    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose the first study of the cold molecular gas in the final assembly phase of a brightest cluster galaxy (BCG) in one of the most distant clusters known XMMXCS J2215.9-1738 at z=1.46, a lookback time of 9 Gyr. Unlike lower redshift clusters this has no obvious BCG but does contain a two (perhaps four) member galaxy major merger in its core, which is a bright mid infrared source with an inferred star formation rate of 250Msol/yr. ALMA is the ideal telescope to study this distant high-mass merger to quantify and map the cold gas that fuels this unique system, which will have major consequences for our understanding of high mass galaxy formation in the densest environments, potentially reconciling observations with theoretical predictions.</prp:abstract>
